{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"byzantine-empire","type":"era","content":{"title":"Byzantine Empire","date_label":"395 CE – 1453 CE","description":"The **Byzantine Empire** — the eastern continuation of the Roman Empire — survived for over a thousand years after the western half collapsed. At its height under Justinian I (527–565), it reconquered much of the Mediterranean world and produced the **Hagia Sophia** and the Justinian Code.\n\nConstantinople served as the wealthiest and most sophisticated city in Europe throughout much of the medieval period. The empire preserved Greco-Roman knowledge, transmitted classical culture to the Islamic world and Renaissance Italy, and defined Eastern Orthodox Christianity.\n\nIts fall to the Ottoman Turks in **1453** is traditionally used to mark the end of the Middle Ages.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["byzantine","roman","constantinople","orthodox","eastern-church"],"sources":[{"title":"Byzantine Empire — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/place/Byzantine-Empire"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"395","end_value":"1453","precision":"year"},"significance":{"value":930,"temporal_scope":"centuries","geographic_scope":"europe-middle-east"}}}
